          "body": "One of the chapter's most striking literary features is the Philistines' speech in verses 7-9. They demonstrate a more accurate theology of the LORD's freedom than Israel's own elders. They know this God struck Egypt with 'all kinds of plagues in the wilderness' (4:8) — mangling the exodus geography slightly, but correctly identifying the LORD as an agent of historic sovereign power. They say 'woe to us' (4:7, 8) — genuine dread. And precisely because they take the LORD seriously, they resolve to fight harder rather than surrender to fatalism. The irony the narrator builds is exquisite: pagans who fear the God of Israel prove to be better strategic reasoners in this moment than the covenant people of that God. Israel shouts with confidence and loses catastrophically (4:10); the Philistines cry 'woe' and fight their way to victory. The episode anticipates the biblical pattern whereby pagan recognition of God's power (Rahab, Naaman, Nebuchadnezzar) sometimes surpasses the covenant community's practiced familiarity with His name."
